3. Interpret the model parameters estimated in part 2, including the estimated variance components. Frame your interpretations with respect to addressing the two research objectives.

I re-centered variable age so that the intercept will represent 8-year-old kids. The model with the five estimated parameters is specified as \[y_{ij}=\beta_0+\beta_1age_{ij}+\mu_{0j}+\mu_{1j}age_{ij}+e_{ij}\]
where j is referred to as each distinct subject and i is each row, representing ages of subjects, in the dataset \[y_{ij}=22.0426+0.6602age_{ij}+\mu_{0j}+\mu_{1j}age_{ij}+e_{ij}\]
1. The estimated mean of distance of cranial is \(\hat{\beta}_0= 22.0426\) (millimeter), holding all other factors constant. With a p-value smaller than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis that the mean distance of cranial is zero.
2. The estimated average of cranial growth (difference of distance) across ages is \(\hat{\beta_1}= 0.6602\) (millimeter), holding all other factors constant. With a p-value smaller than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis that the average growth distance of cranial across ages is zero.
3. The estimated variance of the random child effects is
\(\hat{\sigma}_0^2 = 3.5594\).
4. The estimated variance of the random age effects is \(\hat{\sigma}^2 = 0.0513\).
5. The estimated residual variance is 1.7162.
\[e_{ij}\sim N(0, 1.7162)\]
6. The estimated intra-subject correlation (or ICC) is \(\hat{\rho} = 3.5594/(3.5594 + 0.0513 + 1.7162)= 0.6682\). A large proportion of the differences is explained by different subjects and the growth pattern remains similar within each kid.
7. The estimated correlation between the two random effects, age and the intercept, is 0.21, a weak positive correlation indicating that when age increases, the difference of the distance also increases across subjects.
8. The estimated covariance of the two random effects is 0.0891.
\[ \left( \begin{array}{c} \mu_{0j}\\ \mu_{1j} \end{array} \right) \sim N\left( \left( \begin{array}{c} 0\\ 0 \end{array} \right), \left( \begin{array}{cc} 3.5594&0.0891\\\ 0.0891&0.0513 \end{array} \right) \equiv D \right) \]

4. Test the null hypothesis that the variance of the random AGE effects is equal to zero using a likelihood ratio test. What is the conclusion of this test, again with respect to the research objectives?

mod_4 = lmer(distance ~ age_recenter + (1|subject), REML = T, data = growth)

# Function to calculate LRT p-values for variances of random effects
lrt.pvalue <- function(fit1, fit2) {
  lrtstat <-
    (-2 * as.numeric(summary(fit2)$logLik)) - (-2 * as.numeric(summary(fit1)$logLik))
  pvalue = 0.5 * (1 - pchisq(lrtstat, 2)) + 0.5 * (1 - pchisq(lrtstat, 1))
  return(pvalue)
}
lrt.pvalue(mod_ini, mod_4)
## [1] 0.07468957

With a p-value of 0.0747, which is greater than 0.05, we fail to reject our null hypothesis that the random age effects is equal to zero. Thus, we are not able to exclude the conclusion that cranial growth of children across age 8-14 have similar differences at different ages as the starting points (i.e., the differences between age 8-10, 10-12, and 12-14 within a kid have a linear relationship).

5. Briefly outline how one would perform a similar test of the covariance between the two random effects. You do not need to actually perform this test.

We performed a likelihood ratio test to compare the covariance between the two random effects. Alternatively, one can also compare covariance between the two random effects using an Adaptive Gaussian Quadrature (AGQ) to approximate the likelihood, a Laplace Approximation, or a pseudo-likelihood / penalized quasi-likelihood estimation.

Converting age from continuous variable to categorical allows us to distinguish the means of childrens cranial distances at different ages. In the output, there are three values indicating the differences between age 8, which is the intercept, and the other ages in the data we collected. Visualizing the intercepts, there will be four starting points at 22.1852 mm, 23.1667 mm, 24.6482 mm, and 26.0926 mm. We cannot allow the age effects to randomly vary across children as in the initial model because random effects are usually used for continuous predictors to capture unobserved heterogeneity across levels. However, variations in the effects of age across children can be accounted for by including interaction terms.

8. After deciding whether to include the random age effects in part 7, interpret the parameter estimates from the model fitted in part 7 (and the variance components).

The model with the estimated parameters is specified as
\[y_{ij}=\beta_0+\beta_1age_{10, j}+\beta_2age_{12, j}+\beta_3age_{14, j}+\mu_{0j}+\mu_{1j}age_{ij}+e_{ij}\]
where j is referred to as each subject (row) in the dataset and i is each distinct age
\[y_{ij}=22.1852+0.9815age_{10, j}+2.4630age_{12, j}+3.9074age_{14, j}+\mu_{0j}+\mu_{1j}age_{ij}+e_{ij}\]
1. The estimated mean distance of cranial for child at age 8 is \(\hat{\beta}_0= 22.1852\) (millimeter), holding all other factors constant. With a p-value smaller than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis that the mean distance of cranial at age 8 is zero.
2. The estimated mean distance of cranial for child at age 10 is 23.1667 and \(\hat{\beta}_1= 0.9815\) (millimeter), holding all other factors constant. With a p-value smaller than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis that the mean distance of cranial at age 10 is zero.
3. The estimated mean distance of cranial for child at age 12 is 24.6482 and \(\hat{\beta}_2= 2.4630\) (millimeter), holding all other factors constant. With a p-value smaller than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis that the mean distance of cranial at age 12 is zero.
4. The estimated mean distance of cranial for child at age 14 is 26.0926 and \(\hat{\beta}_3= 3.9074\) (millimeter), holding all other factors constant. With a p-value smaller than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis that the mean distance of cranial at age 14 is zero.
5. The estimated variance of the random child effects is
\(\hat{\sigma}_0^2 = 3.5378\).
4. The estimated variance of the random age effects is \(\hat{\sigma}^2 = 0.0497\).
5. The estimated residual variance is \[e_{ij}\sim N(0, 1.747)\].
6. The estimated intra-subject correlation (or ICC) is \(\hat{\rho} = 3.5378/(3.5378+0.0497+1.747)= 0.6632\). A large proportion of the differences is explained by different subjects and the growth pattern remains similar within each kid across ages.
7. The estimated correlation between the two random effects, age and the intercept, is 0.22, a weak positive correlation indicating that when age increases, the difference of the distance also increases.
8. The estimated covariance of the two random effects is 0.0937. \[ \left( \begin{array}{c} \mu_{0j}\\ \mu_{1j} \end{array} \right) \sim N\left( \left( \begin{array}{c} 0\\ 0 \end{array} \right), \left( \begin{array}{cc} 3.5378&0.0937\\\ 0.0937&0.0497 \end{array} \right) \equiv D \right) \]

10. Write a page summary of the methods and results of the above analyses, with specific regard to the two study objectives. Make sure to be clear about the estimation methods and software used.

For this multilevel model data analysis, I used R packages including lme4, nlme, lmerTest, and tidyverse to perform estimations of models.

I started with data visualization to examine variables that are valuable to look at their distributions for diagnostics after building models. With the distributions looking good, I built an initial model containing distance as the dependent variable with a fixed intercept, a fixed effect of age, a random effect associated with the intercept for each child, and a random effect associated with age for each child. I reported the estimated parameters, their standard errors, the significance tests, and the estimated covariance of the two random effects in my model. The regression model is \[y_{ij}=22.0426+0.6602age_{ij}+\mu_{0j}+\mu_{1j}age_{ij}+e_{ij}\]and the ICC is .6682, where each child explains more of the difference in terms of the distance from the center of the pituitary to the pteryo-maxillary fissure in mm comparing to different ages. However, with a p-value of 0.0747, we fail to reject our null hypothesis that the random age effects is equal to zero, indicating that we are not able to conclude that cranial growth of children across age 8-14 have similar differences at different ages as the starting points.

I then built a second model, adding gender and the interaction term of age and gender to determine whether child gender explains variability in the linear age effects across children. The regression model concludes as \[y_{ij}=21.2091+0.4795age_{ij}+1.4065gender_{M, j}+0.3048age_{ij}gender_{M, j}+\mu_{0j}+\mu_{1j}age_{ij}+e_{ij}\]and the ICC is .6533. The percentage of variance in random effects of age explained by adding gender and the interaction term is 71.978%. This result suggests that gender and the interaction term with age are important factors in explaining why the effects of age vary across different subjects.

Next, I convert age from continuous variable to categorical so that it allows us to distinguish the means of childrens cranial distances at different ages. The regression model looks like \[y_{ij}=22.1852+0.9815age_{10, j}+2.4630age_{12, j}+3.9074age_{14, j}+\mu_{0j}+\mu_{1j}age_{ij}+e_{ij}\]and the ICC is .6632. Visualizing the output, there will be four starting points at 22.1852 mm, 23.1667 mm, 24.6482 mm, and 26.0926 mm with ages of 8, 10, 12, and 14, respectively. However, converting this independent variable does not allow the age effects to randomly vary across children because random effects are usually used for continuous predictors to capture unobserved heterogeneity across levels. Nonetheless, variations in the effects of age across children can be accounted for by including interaction terms.

After the three multilevel models, I complete a simple diagnostic with some normal Q-Q plots and the results reveal that both the first and the last model achieve our assumptions including no observed relationship between the fitted values and the residuals and the normally-distributed residuals, intercepts, and the slopes. The AIC values indicate that the initial model I built is actually better than the last model.

In conclusion, to answer the two research objectives, different age start points do share similar growth pattern in terms of the distance from the center of the pituitary to the pteryo-maxillary fissure within each kid. In addition, kids (i.e., subjects) are non-neglectable in explaining the differences of growth rates. Among the three models, about 60-80% of the trajectories are explained by subject. Lastly, gender is also helpful in explaining the variance of trajectories among children.
